> On 29/03/2026 08:48 pm, CEO wrote:
>>
>> Dear SPINRISE Team,
>>
>> I am sharing with you today a guide that I have personally put 
>> together with the assistance of Claude.
>>
>> The document is attached: SPINRISE VB FSD Claude Guide v1.docx
>>
>> *Please read it fully at your own pace and share your feedback, at 
>> the earliest.*
>>
>> *What this guide is*
>>
>> This guide explains, in plain English, how each of us uses Claude to 
>> convert a VB6 screen into a Form Specification Document (FSD) — and 
>> how that FSD then travels through our four-level review chain before 
>> it is used to generate the new SPINRISE web screen.
>>
>> It covers:
>>   • What an FSD is and why we need one for every VB6 screen
>>   • The complete five-step process for the Module VB Developer
>>   • The exact Claude prompt to use — ready to copy and paste
>>   • The three follow-up questions to always ask Claude after the 
>> first output
>>   • The four-level review chain: Module Sr IST → TL-IST → PM → CEO
>>   • What each reviewer specifically checks and signs off
>>   • Quick reference cards you can print and keep at your desk
>>
>> *Who should read which sections
>> *
>> *Module VB Developers:*
>> Section 3 is your primary reference. It walks you through all five 
>> steps with the exact prompt, the before-and-after example showing VB6 
>> code versus Claude’s plain-English output, and the three follow-up 
>> questions. Read this section carefully before you begin your first 
>> FSD. The quick reference card in Section 7 is your daily desk guide.
>>
>> *Module Sr IST Members:*
>> Section 4, Level 1 is written for you. It explains exactly what your 
>> review covers, how to write your annotations in the Word document 
>> using the [IST ADD] and [IST CONFIRMED] tags, and what you must sign 
>> off before the FSD moves to TL-IST.
>>
>> *TL-IST:*
>> Section 4, Level 2 is your reference. You are the second domain gate 
>> — the overall domain validation after the Module Sr IST has done the 
>> first check. Your experience across all modules and all customer 
>> sites is what this level brings to the FSD.
>>
>> *Project Manager:*
>> Section 4, Level 3. Your role is completeness — not domain accuracy. 
>> By the time the FSD reaches you, the domain has been validated by two 
>> levels. Your question is: is this document thorough enough for a 
>> developer to build the screen from scratch without any ambiguity?
>>
>> *CEO:*
>> Section 4, Level 4 and Section 6. The CEO review is the final domain 
>> authority gate. No technical skill is needed. Only the question: does 
>> this FSD accurately reflect how the business process was designed to 
>> work, and does it carry forward the knowledge that has been built 
>> over decades of spinning ERP implementation?
>>
>> *A personal note*
>>
>> This process — Document, Validate, Convert — is the quality backbone 
>> of SPINRISE. Every web screen we build is only as good as the FSD 
>> behind it.
>>
>> I have been saying this since we began: we are not just migrating a 
>> software platform. We are converting decades of accumulated spinning 
>> ERP knowledge into a permanent, structured form that will outlast the 
>> technology it runs on. Each FSD that is reviewed and approved is a 
>> piece of that knowledge preserved correctly.
>>
>> I want every one of you to understand the process fully — not just 
>> the step that applies to your role, but the complete journey from VB6 
>> code to live SPINRISE web screen. When everyone understands the full 
>> chain, every handover between roles becomes cleaner, faster, and more 
>> accurate.
>>
>> *What I need from you*
>>
>> Read the guide before this Saturday’s session.
>>
>> If any step is unclear, any instruction is ambiguous, or any section 
>> does not match what you experience in practice — write it down. 
>> *Share your feedback as reply to this mail.*
>>
>> This is version 1. Your feedback will shape version 2.
>>
>> With confidence in the team,
>> T Mani
>>
>> Attachment: SPINRISE_VB_FSD_Claude_Guide_v1.docx
>>
