      <div class="moz-cite-prefix">On 29/03/2026 08:48 pm, CEO wrote:<br>
      </div>
      <blockquote type="cite"
        cite="mid:036f0737-960e-488e-b84c-8142e9220927@kalsofte.com">
        <meta http-equiv="content-type"
          content="text/html; charset=UTF-8">
        <p>Dear SPINRISE Team,<br>
          <br>
          I am sharing with you today a guide that I have personally put
          together with the assistance of Claude.<br>
          <br>
          The document is attached: SPINRISE VB FSD Claude Guide v1.docx<br>
          <br>
          <b>Please read it fully at your own pace and share your
            feedback, at the earliest.</b></p>
        <p><font size="4"><b>What this guide is</b></font><br>
          <br>
          This guide explains, in plain English, how each of us uses
          Claude to convert a VB6 screen into a Form Specification
          Document (FSD) — and how that FSD then travels through our
          four-level review chain before it is used to generate the new
          SPINRISE web screen.<br>
          <br>
          It covers:<br>
            • What an FSD is and why we need one for every VB6 screen<br>
            • The complete five-step process for the Module VB Developer<br>
            • The exact Claude prompt to use — ready to copy and paste<br>
            • The three follow-up questions to always ask Claude after
          the first output<br>
            • The four-level review chain: Module Sr IST → TL-IST → PM →
          CEO<br>
            • What each reviewer specifically checks and signs off<br>
            • Quick reference cards you can print and keep at your desk<br>
          <br>
          <font size="4"><b>Who should read which sections<br>
            </b></font><br>
          <b>Module VB Developers:</b><br>
          Section 3 is your primary reference. It walks you through all
          five steps with the exact prompt, the before-and-after example
          showing VB6 code versus Claude’s plain-English output, and the
          three follow-up questions. Read this section carefully before
          you begin your first FSD. The quick reference card in Section
          7 is your daily desk guide.<br>
          <br>
          <b>Module Sr IST Members:</b><br>
          Section 4, Level 1 is written for you. It explains exactly
          what your review covers, how to write your annotations in the
          Word document using the [IST ADD] and [IST CONFIRMED] tags,
          and what you must sign off before the FSD moves to TL-IST.<br>
          <br>
          <b>TL-IST:</b><br>
          Section 4, Level 2 is your reference. You are the second
          domain gate — the overall domain validation after the Module
          Sr IST has done the first check. Your experience across all
          modules and all customer sites is what this level brings to
          the FSD.<br>
          <br>
          <b>Project Manager:</b><br>
          Section 4, Level 3. Your role is completeness — not domain
          accuracy. By the time the FSD reaches you, the domain has been
          validated by two levels. Your question is: is this document
          thorough enough for a developer to build the screen from
          scratch without any ambiguity?<br>
          <br>
          <b>CEO:</b><br>
          Section 4, Level 4 and Section 6. The CEO review is the final
          domain authority gate. No technical skill is needed. Only the
          question: does this FSD accurately reflect how the business
          process was designed to work, and does it carry forward the
          knowledge that has been built over decades of spinning ERP
          implementation?<br>
          <br>
          <font size="4"><b>A personal note</b></font><br>
          <br>
          This process — Document, Validate, Convert — is the quality
          backbone of SPINRISE. Every web screen we build is only as
          good as the FSD behind it.<br>
          <br>
          I have been saying this since we began: we are not just
          migrating a software platform. We are converting decades of
          accumulated spinning ERP knowledge into a permanent,
          structured form that will outlast the technology it runs on.
          Each FSD that is reviewed and approved is a piece of that
          knowledge preserved correctly.<br>
          <br>
          I want every one of you to understand the process fully — not
          just the step that applies to your role, but the complete
          journey from VB6 code to live SPINRISE web screen. When
          everyone understands the full chain, every handover between
          roles becomes cleaner, faster, and more accurate.<br>
          <br>
          <b><font size="4">What I need from you</font></b><br>
          <br>
          Read the guide before this Saturday’s session.<br>
          <br>
          If any step is unclear, any instruction is ambiguous, or any
          section does not match what you experience in practice — write
          it down. <b>Share your feedback as reply to this mail.</b><br>
          <br>
          This is version 1. Your feedback will shape version 2.<br>
          <br>
          With confidence in the team,<br>
          T Mani<br>
          <br>
          Attachment: SPINRISE_VB_FSD_Claude_Guide_v1.docx</p>
      </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
  </body>
